<paragraph blockId="27.[130,775,729,832]" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">
OCCURRENCE. — Upper Ordovician of 
<collectingCountry box="[503,628,729,753]" name="United States of America" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">United States</collectingCountry>
and Europe. La Pola Formation, Upper Ordovician, Sandbian; La Pola creek section near Albardon village, 
<collectingRegion box="[351,531,782,806]" country="Argentina" name="San Juan" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">San Juan Province</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[541,637,782,806]" name="Argentina" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">Argentine</collectingCountry>
Precordillera, western 
<collectingCountry box="[213,313,808,832]" name="Argentina" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">Argentina</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="588" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="27.[131,777,885,1580]" box="[132,277,885,911]" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[131,777,885,1580]" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">
Branched bifoliate, dichotomous colonies. Branches flattened, with sharp edges, 
<quantity box="[429,600,948,975]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.825" metricValueMax="3.25" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="2.825" valueMax="3.25" valueMin="2.4">2.40-3.25 mm</quantity>
wide and 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.4" valueMin="0.9">0.9- 1.4 mm</quantity>
thick. Mesotheca three-layered, straight both in longitudinal and transverse sections, containing abundant median rods, 
<quantity box="[290,455,1044,1071]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.04" valueMax="0.05" valueMin="0.03">0.03-0.05 mm</quantity>
thick. Median rods densely spaced, 
<quantity box="[223,414,1076,1103]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.65" metricValueMax="3.8" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.0265" valueMax="0.038" valueMin="0.015">
<geoCoordinate box="[223,289,1076,1103]" degrees="0.015" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" precision="55" value="0.015">0.015</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate box="[289,362,1076,1103]" degrees="0.038" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" precision="55" value="-0.038">-0.038</geoCoordinate>
mm
</quantity>
in diameter, continuous in dark zones separating longitudinal rows of autozooecia. Autozooecia regularly arranged in 10-14 alternating longitudinal rows, semicircular to trapezoid in transverse section in endozone, rectangular in deep tangential section, becoming oval on the colony surface. Autozooecial diaphragms common, straight. Autozooecial walls laminated, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.02" valueMax="0.025" valueMin="0.015">
<geoCoordinate box="[702,769,1267,1294]" degrees="0.015" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" precision="55" value="0.015">0.015</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate degrees="0.025" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" precision="55" value="-0.025">- 0.025</geoCoordinate>
mm
</quantity>
thick in endozones. Autozooecial boundaries distinct, delineated laterally by continuous dark zones. Extrazooecial skeletal deposits well developed, consisting of laminar and vesicular portions. Laminar stereom with dark zones, longitudinally aligned, separating autozooecia in exozones, containing abundant mural styles. Mural styles 
<quantity box="[131,293,1491,1517]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.03" valueMax="0.04" valueMin="0.02">0.02-0.04 mm</quantity>
in diameter. Vesicular structures small and sparse, having flat to rounded roofs, rare to common on branch edges.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[131,777,1618,2028]" box="[133,277,1618,1644]" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">COMPARISON</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="588" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="27.[131,777,1618,2028]" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">
<taxonomicName authority="(Ulrich, 1893)" baseAuthorityName="Ulrich" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[132,533,1650,1676]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Rhinidictyidae" genus="Trigonodictya" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cryptostomida" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis box="[132,363,1650,1676]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">Trigonodictya elegans</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="ULRICH E. O." box="[376,525,1650,1676]" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" pagination="96 - 332" refId="ref23237" refString="ULRICH E. O. 1893. - On Lower Silurian Bryozoa of Minnesota. The Geological and Natural History Survey of Minnesota, final report 3: 96 - 332. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 56338" type="book chapter" year="1893">Ulrich, 1893</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Karklins, 1983" authorityName="Karklins" authorityYear="1983" class="Stenolaemata" family="Rhinidictyidae" genus="Trigonodictya" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cryptostomida" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="cirrita">
<emphasis box="[676,774,1651,1676]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">T. cirrita</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="KARKLINS O. L." box="[132,309,1682,1708]" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" pagination="1 - 31" refId="ref21104" refString="KARKLINS O. L. 1983 a. - Ptilodictyoid cryptostomate Bryozoa from the Middle and Upper Ordovician rocks of Central Kentucky. Memoirs of the Paleontological Society 14: 1 - 31. https: // www. jstor. org / stable / 1315533" type="journal article" year="1983">Karklins, 1983</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from the Upper Ordovician of 
<collectingCountry name="United States of America" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">United States</collectingCountry>
and from the Las Plantas and Las Aguaditas formations (Sandbian) of 
<collectingCountry box="[401,517,1746,1772]" name="Argentina" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, but differs from it in smaller autozooecial apertures (average aperture width 
<quantity box="[132,235,1810,1836]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.11">0.11 mm</quantity>
vs 
<quantity box="[269,372,1810,1836]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.14">0.14 mm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karklins" authorityYear="1983" box="[405,502,1810,1835]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Rhinidictyidae" genus="Trigonodictya" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cryptostomida" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="cirrita">
<emphasis box="[405,502,1810,1835]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">T. cirrita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and in larger distances between aperture centres (at average 
<quantity box="[536,637,1841,1868]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5999999999999996" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.36">0.36 mm</quantity>
vs 
<quantity box="[671,773,1842,1868]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.42">0.42 mm</quantity>
in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Karklins" authorityYear="1983" box="[165,266,1874,1899]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Rhinidictyidae" genus="Trigonodictya" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cryptostomida" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="cirrita">
<emphasis box="[165,266,1874,1899]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">T. cirrita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ulrich" baseAuthorityYear="1893" box="[293,527,1873,1899]" class="Stenolaemata" family="Rhinidictyidae" genus="Trigonodictya" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cryptostomida" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="elegans">
<emphasis box="[293,527,1873,1899]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">Trigonodictya elegans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hall, 1847)" baseAuthorityName="Hall" baseAuthorityYear="1847" class="Stenolaemata" family="Rhinidictyidae" genus="Trigonodictya" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cryptostomida" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" phylum="Bryozoa" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis box="[686,777,1874,1899]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">T. acuta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="HALL J." box="[141,268,1905,1931]" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" refId="ref20633" refString="HALL J. 1847. - Graptolites of the Inferior strata of the New York system. Palaeontology of New York. Volume 1. Van Benthuysen, Albany, New York, 338 p. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 66970" type="book" year="1847">Hall, 1847</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from the Middle Ordovician of 
<collectingRegion box="[654,770,1905,1932]" country="United States of America" name="New York" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">New York</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[133,290,1937,1963]" name="United States of America" pageId="27" pageNumber="588">United States</collectingCountry>
, but differs from it in smaller autozooecial apertures (aperture width 
<quantity box="[419,580,1969,1996]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.11499999999999999" valueMax="0.15" valueMin="0.08">0.08-0.15 mm</quantity>
vs 
<quantity box="[613,775,1969,1996]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="27" pageNumber="588" unit="mm" value="0.13" valueMax="0.16" valueMin="0.1">0.10-0.16 mm</quantity>
